{"title_page": "Russell Sherman", "text_new": "'''Russell Sherman''' (born March 25, 1930, [[New York, New York]]) is an American classical pianist, educator and author.\n\nRussell Sherman made his debut at [[The Town Hall (New York City)|The Town Hall]] in New York at age 15, later studying piano with [[Edward Steuermann]] and composition with [[Erich Itor Kahn]]. Sherman has performed as a piano soloist with the [[New York Philharmonic]], the [[Los Angeles Philharmonic]], the [[Boston Symphony Orchestra]], the [[Chicago Symphony Orchestra]], and the [[Philadelphia Orchestra]]. He has performed in recital throughout the United States, Europe, South America, and the former Soviet Union.\n\nHe is currently artist-in-residence at [[New England Conservatory]], where over thirty years ago he met and instructed Wha Kyung Byun, a woman who later became a well-known piano instructor herself as well as his wife.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.boston.com/news/globe/living/articles/2004/05/02/recital_is_a_chance_to_listen_to_the_teacher/ | last = Dyer | first = Richard | title = Recital is a chance to listen to the teacher: Piano instructor Wha Kyung Byun gives rare concert | publisher = Boston Globe | date = May 2, 2004 | accessdate = 2009-07-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.boston.com/news/globe/living/articles/2004/05/07/pianists_unique_styles_form_a_perfect_union/ | title = Pianists' unique styles form a perfect union | last = Dyer | first = Richard | date = May 7, 2004 | work = Boston Globe | accessdate= 2009-07-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title = Newsmakers, 1987: Cumulation | edition = 87 | editors = Evory, Ann, Peter M. Gareffa | publisher = Gale Group | year = 1988 | isbn= 0-8103-2203-X | page = 331}}</ref>\n\nSherman's efforts as an educator have produced a number of pianists of note, among them, [[Marc-Andr\u00e9 Hamelin]], [[Christopher O'Riley]], Tian Ying, Keren Hanan, HaeSun Paik, [[Ning An]], Hung-Kuan Chen, Minsoo Sohn, [[Christopher Taylor (pianist)|Christopher Taylor]], Hugh Hinton, [[Soojin Ahn]], Randall Hodgkinson, Zenan Yu, Rina Dokshitsky, Livan, [[Sergey Schepkin]], [[Kathleen Supov\u00e9]], and [[Craig Smith (conductor)|Craig Smith]].<ref>{{cite news | first= | last= | title=Is Russell Sherman a Great Teacher? Here Are Six Nights of Proof | date=2003-11-30| work =The New York Times | pages =  }}</ref>\n\nSherman's book of short essays on piano playing related concerns, \"Piano Pieces,\" was published by [[Farrar, Straus and Giroux]] in 1996. Among the observations in \"Piano Pieces\" is Sherman's comment that, \"Music dispels the fear of mortality and the need for rigid and permanent identities. Music rejects the nine-to-five schedule, the hunger for cash, the encroachments and limits of crass appetite.\"<ref>{{cite book | last = Sherman | first = Russell | authorlink =  | title = Piano Pieces | publisher = Northpoint Press; Farrar, Straus and Giroux | year = 1996 | location = New York, New York | pages =  | url = https://archive.org/details/pianopieces00sher | doi =  | id =  | isbn = 0-374-23206-7 | url-access = registration }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.newenglandconservatory.edu/faculty/shermanR.html Russell Sherman's New England Conservatory faculty page]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3WXGRRyw5rc David Dubal interview with Russell Sherman], WNCN-FM, 11-Nov-1984\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sherman, Russell}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American classical pianists]]\n[[Category:American male pianists]]\n[[Category:American music educators]]\n[[Category:New England Conservatory faculty]]\n[[Category:Jewish classical pianists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American pianists]]\n[[Category:21st-century classical pianists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American pianists]]\n", "text_old": "'''Russell Sherman''' (born March 25, 1930, [[New York, New York]]) is an American classical pianist, educator and author.\n\nRussell Sherman made his debut at [[The Town Hall (New York City)|The Town Hall]] in New York at age 15, later studying piano with [[Edward Steuermann]] and composition with [[Erich Itor Kahn]]. Sherman has performed as a piano soloist with the [[New York Philharmonic]], the [[Los Angeles Philharmonic]], the [[Boston Symphony Orchestra]], the [[Chicago Symphony Orchestra]], and the [[Philadelphia Orchestra]]. He has performed in recital throughout the United States, Europe, South America, and the former Soviet Union.\n\nHe is currently artist-in-residence at [[New England Conservatory]], where over thirty years ago he met and instructed Wha Kyung Byun, a woman who later became a well-known piano instructor herself as well as his wife.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.boston.com/news/globe/living/articles/2004/05/02/recital_is_a_chance_to_listen_to_the_teacher/ | last = Dyer | first = Richard | title = Recital is a chance to listen to the teacher: Piano instructor Wha Kyung Byun gives rare concert | publisher = Boston Globe | date = May 2, 2004 | accessdate = 2009-07-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.boston.com/news/globe/living/articles/2004/05/07/pianists_unique_styles_form_a_perfect_union/ | title = Pianists' unique styles form a perfect union | last = Dyer | first = Richard | date = May 7, 2004 | work = Boston Globe | accessdate= 2009-07-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title = Newsmakers, 1987: Cumulation | edition = 87 | editors = Evory, Ann, Peter M. Gareffa | publisher = Gale Group | year = 1988 | isbn= 0-8103-2203-X | page = 331}}</ref>\n\nSherman's efforts as an educator have produced a number of pianists of note, among them, [[Marc-Andr\u00e9 Hamelin]], [[Christopher O'Riley]], Tian Ying, [[Keren Hanan]], HaeSun Paik, [[Ning An]], Hung-Kuan Chen, Minsoo Sohn, [[Christopher Taylor (pianist)|Christopher Taylor]], Hugh Hinton, [[Soojin Ahn]], Randall Hodgkinson, Zenan Yu, Rina Dokshitsky, Livan, [[Sergey Schepkin]], [[Kathleen Supov\u00e9]], and [[Craig Smith (conductor)|Craig Smith]].<ref>{{cite news | first= | last= | title=Is Russell Sherman a Great Teacher? Here Are Six Nights of Proof | date=2003-11-30| work =The New York Times | pages =  }}</ref>\n\nSherman's book of short essays on piano playing related concerns, \"Piano Pieces,\" was published by [[Farrar, Straus and Giroux]] in 1996. Among the observations in \"Piano Pieces\" is Sherman's comment that, \"Music dispels the fear of mortality and the need for rigid and permanent identities. Music rejects the nine-to-five schedule, the hunger for cash, the encroachments and limits of crass appetite.\"<ref>{{cite book | last = Sherman | first = Russell | authorlink =  | title = Piano Pieces | publisher = Northpoint Press; Farrar, Straus and Giroux | year = 1996 | location = New York, New York | pages =  | url = https://archive.org/details/pianopieces00sher | doi =  | id =  | isbn = 0-374-23206-7 | url-access = registration }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.newenglandconservatory.edu/faculty/shermanR.html Russell Sherman's New England Conservatory faculty page]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3WXGRRyw5rc David Dubal interview with Russell Sherman], WNCN-FM, 11-Nov-1984\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sherman, Russell}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American classical pianists]]\n[[Category:American male pianists]]\n[[Category:American music educators]]\n[[Category:New England Conservatory faculty]]\n[[Category:Jewish classical pianists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American pianists]]\n[[Category:21st-century classical pianists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American pianists]]\n", "name_user": "Sandstein", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Ar